The payback period of a company can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Payback period}&=\text{Years before break-even}+\dfrac{\text{Amount to be recovered}}{\text{Net cashflow in recovery years}}
\end{aligned}$$

To get the years before break-even, we can simply count the number of years before the cash flow exceeds the Year 0 or initial cashflow of the investment.

From this, we can see that there are 2 years before Investment A reaches break-even, while Investment B will take 3 years.

We can now solve for the payback period of each of the investments using the formula in Step 2.

For Investment A:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Payback period}&=2+\dfrac{\$16,000}{\$17,000}\\[15 pt]
&=2.94\ \text{years}
\end{aligned}$$

For Investment B:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Payback period}&=3+\dfrac{\$5,000}{\$16,000}\\[15 pt]
&=3.31\ \text{years}
\end{aligned}$$

Here, we can see that only Investment A fits the payback cutoff of the company which means that the company should accept Investment A.
